td.content:
Plantar fasciitis is inflammation of the thick band of tissue (also called a fascia) at the bottom of your foot that runs from your heel to your toes. Heel spurs are the result -- not the cause -- of plantar fasciitis. Causes include bad shoes, going barefoot, foot mechanics, exercises, and a gain in weight. Home Treatment: Wear shoes with arch support at all times (no barefoot), reduce activity, stretching, icing and NSAIDS if tolerated. Other treatments include cortisone injections, prescribed meds, physical therapy and, in rare cases, surgery.
TENDONITIS POSTERIOR TIBIAL: The posterior tibial muscle and tendon help stabilize the ankle. They are responsible for pointing the foot in and down. Posterior tibial tendinopathy includes both ?tendonitis? (a condition involving inflammation of the tendon) and ?tendinosis? (a condition involving degeneration of the tendon over time). For the majority of athletes, such as in runners, dysfunction of the tendon occurs gradually due to overuse and over-pronation (flattening of the foot). It can also occur suddenly due to overloading of the tendon. In both cases, individuals with flat feet (a condition known as pes planus) are more prone to this condition.
Sinus Tarsi Syndrome: This syndrome is an opening in the boney tissue in the middle of two bones with the hind part of the foot beneath the ankle joint. The structures that are in between these two bones will have also been sprained during a twisted out ankle joint strain. But at first this will get missed or will not be identified
